<Author>Kimblypeg
<Content>Changing my mind about Radissons... As a frequent business traveler who has high expectations for my hotel stays, I tend to book or avoid the same hotel chains based on my experiences there. For a long time, I avoided Radissons as a chain because I had many bad experiences with their brand, especially in the area of customer service.However, with my company booking travel, I sometimes have no choice in where I stay, and that is how I ended up at the Radisson in Boston. And boy am I glad I did! In the past my favorite hotels in Boston have been the Doubletree downtown, and the Tremont (currently owned by Courtyard by Mariott). But the Radisson blows them away. The rooms are a beautiful size, with balconies, and both a desk area and a sitting area. Additionally, there is a small shelf in an alcove just inside the door for the coffee machine and ice--a nice touch that other hotels would do well to adopt. I'm always frustrated by having to have my coffee machine on my desk or in my bathroom. The only thing that would improve the room would be a small fridge  microwave--with all the great restaurants downtown and a week long stay, I had a lot of leftovers that I would love to have kept and reheated for snacks.The bathroom seemed almost new, with an extraordinarily deep tub, and hallelujah, a bathrobe--again, a simple touch that ups the class of the room several notches. Service was prompt and professional, yet not intrusive, and the location cannot be beat.The fitness room is not spectacular, nor is the pool (no whirlpool or sauna), but both are adequate for the business traveler or casual workout.The location is fantastic, within easy walking or transit to everything you want to do in Boston. I highly recommend this hotel, and would come back here for a leisure stay. I'm hoping more of the Radissons that I will stay at this year are even half as nice as this one. 
