<Content>Excellent staff, Great location My wife and I had planned our trip to Boston to coincide with the 4th of July celebrations. We arrived at the 鈥楻adisson Hotel Boston鈥?on the 3rd July after a long day travelling from Memphis, only to be told that they didn鈥檛 have a non-smoking room available for us, but that we could walk across the street to the Park Plaza where they would put us up instead for that night (unfortunately not for both nights). We could then check back in to the Radisson as soon as we leave the Plaza the next day, and we can also have complementary breakfast. So armed with the prospect of a free meal in the morning, we checked in at the Park Plaza for one night.I couldn't complain too much as I had booked the hotel trough Priceline (which does not guarantee the room type). Nevertheless the young lady at the desk offered us a junior suite for the inconvenience for our second night. They locked our luggage away after we took our overnight bags with us.We checked out of the Park Plaza the next day and walked across to the Radisson, where we were told that they didn鈥檛 have a room ready for us yet鈥?So off we went for our free breakfast (which was lunch by this time) and by the time we finished, the room was ready. They gave us a nice Junior Suite, which was very pleasant. The 'Sleep number' beds are quite good - much better than any of the other hotel beds we had on our trip.The concierge was very helpful, arranging a rental car (Dollar) to be brought to the hotel and allowing us to return it at our next hotel when we god back from Cape Cod in a few days time (the Royal Sonesta - excellent hotel, see my other review). He was very sympathetic when we told him that we were awoken at 6:45 in the morning by a fire alarm at the Park Plaza and he arranged for us to have complementary breakfast the following day.There are a number of good restaurants within a short walking distance of the hotel and it is close to the 'T' so transport is good too. The bell 