<Content>Very good location, nice views, and good price The Radisson in Boston is in an ideal location. It is only a short walk from either the Arlington or Boylston Street T Stations on the green line, as well as Boston Commons, Back Bay, Legal Sea Foods (across the street) and as a bonus, if you take the trolley tour (you should) which introduces you to Boston and the Freedom Trail, it specifically stops right in front of the Radisson as a routine stop. I think it was 27 bucks a day, 10 for any subsequent day. You get off and on as many times as you please between 9 and 5 and it hits every place you've heard of in Boston except Fenway. You'll need the subway for that. Ask the Concierge where to buy it. I won't argue with some of the other users who complain about a somewhat abrasive staff at the Radisson, that is why I only gave it four stars, but they weren't that bad. They would be considered downright friendly if they were in New York. Another bonus is balconies for every room. Ask for the West facing side of the hotel for great views of the John Hancock tower, Prudential tower, and South Boston (as well as nice sunsets on cloudy days). The on-premises restaurant is quite good, offering a breakfast buffet (or menu items) and good food other times too. Room did smell like smoke even though it was non-smoking, couldn't say why that is, but you might be prepared for the possibility if it bothers you. Hotel offers parking, and rapes you for it at 28 bucks a day, but hey, that's the Big City. I think it's fairly typical, really. Don't keep a car in Boston if you can avoid it, you won't need it. If you drive in as I did, go with Hertz or Budget, as they are across the street from the Hotel, but a challenge to find. Drive in front of the hotel and make the first possible left-hander just as you see Legal Sea Foods on your left. Car rental is on your left about 100 feet after the turn. I mention this because it took me an hour to find it the first time, as if they tried to hide it. Yes, I know there is no place to park either when dropping off a car, double-park it. Even Budget will tell you to do so, and a cop watched me, unphased. Try this hotel, it's not luxury, but it is upscale, with nice rooms, and a very convenient location. Overall, very good for the price. Just across the way, the Park Plaza might be a good bet for higher end accommodations, all of the last six presidents have stayed there, supposedly. In Boston, don't underestimate the location, this one is very good. I do recommend this place for affordable Boston accommodations that are very nice and in a convenient location. 
