<Author>gsnichol
<Content>Nice place, big rooms! I stayed here for four nights in September 2003. I booked on expedia and got an excellent deal, saving several hundred pounds on what I would have been charged had I paid Radisson's normal rate for the room. If you're looking at a map while reading this, the hotel is on Stuart Street, diagonally opposite the Massachusetts Transportation Building. Got to the hotel by taxi - $26 - but found out that it is only about two minutes from Arlington T stop which is only $1! So that's an option, especially if you have been to Boston before and don't have a lot of luggage. Our room was on the 11th floor, which sounds high, but the first 8 are taken up by a multi-storey car park! The hotel has 24 floors. Room was huge, two very comfortable queen-sized beds, and enormous television, clock radio and good chairs and tables. You also get a free copy of USA Today (useless for European news...) delievered outside your door every morning, Spotless bathroom with one of those odd hotel baths that isn't actually big enough to have a bath in at all. Hot, powerful shower though. All rooms have a balcony which give views either towards the Financial District and the harbour (and airport!) or to Back Bay and the John Hancock Tower. The hotel pool is small - max depth 5ft and you couldn't practice for the Olympics in it - but it is fine for a bit of relaxation after a long day. The gym had quite a lot of stuff in it too. There is also a sun terrace on the pool level, with loungers, chairs, tables and a lovely view towards Back Bay and southern Boston.There are plenty of restaurants on the street outside which were decent and well-priced so you don't have to wander around looking for something to eat when you arrive (beware 7 11 at night though - there are guys purporting to be homeless who stand outside the door and open it for you, shaking their cup of coins as they do. To avoid them, go there during the day). It's also about 10 minutes walk in one direction to the shopping centres at the Prudential Tower and Copley Plaza, and in the other direction there are plenty of theatres to keep you amused. Mariah Carey was singing there when we arrived - alas we couldn't hear her from outside...Other reviewers mention the T - to be frank, there's little need to take it! It's one block to Boston common and from there you can wander to downtown, so if you're good on your feet you won't need to use the T at all. We used it once - when we returned from the shopping centre in Cambridge laden with bags!We also had breakfast at the hotel. At $14 for a hot buffet (the best value option), that's quite cheap for a hotel breakfast. Plenty of choice, excellent staff, decent food although the toaster took some working out!In all, if you can get a good deal from expedia or some other website for this hotel, it is well worth booking.PS - other reviewers mention the dirt stains on the carpet. We had them too! Don't let this make you think the carpets hadn't seen a hoover though; they were vacuumed every day. The carpets are light green, which unfortunately means someone spilling coffee, tea or any other coloured drink will mark the carpet. The carpets are clean, just dyed a little! 
